name.text: Solve the quadratic equation either by factoring or the quadratic formula

questiontext.text:
Solve the quadratic equation \({@quest@} = 0\). Enter your answers in the boxes below.

If the equation has a double root enter the double root twice.

\(x =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] or \(x = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]

[[feedback:prt1]]

generalfeedback.text:
Worked solution

We will consider two ways to approach this question.


Method 1 - Factorising:

\({@quest@} = 0\)

\({@(x-pm1*aa)*(x-pm2*bb)@} = 0\)

\({@x-pm1*aa@} = 0\) or \({@x-pm2*bb@} = 0\)

\(x = {@pm1*aa@}\) or \(x = {@pm2*bb@}\)


Method 2 - Quadratic Formula:

\({@quest@} = 0\)

\(a = 1\), \(b = {@-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@}\) and \(c = {@pm1*aa*pm2*bb@}\)

\(x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\)

\(= \frac{-{@blb@} {@-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} {@brb@} \pm \sqrt{{@blb@} {@-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} {@brb@}^2-4\cdot 1 \cdot {@clb@} {@pm1*aa*pm2*bb@} {@crb@}}}{2\cdot 1}\)

\(= \frac{{@(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} \pm \sqrt{{@(-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb))^2@}- {@clb@} {@4*pm1*aa*pm2*bb@} {@crb@}}}{2}\)

\(= \frac{{@(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} \pm \sqrt{{@(-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb))^2-4*pm1*aa*pm2*bb@}}}{2}\)

\(\displaystyle = \frac{{@(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} \pm {@sqrt((-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb))^2-4*pm1*aa*pm2*bb)@}}{2}\)

\(\displaystyle x= \frac{{@(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} + {@sqrt((-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb))^2-4*pm1*aa*pm2*bb)@}}{2}\) or \(\displaystyle x= \frac{{@(pm1*aa+pm2*bb)@} - {@sqrt((-(pm1*aa+pm2*bb))^2-4*pm1*aa*pm2*bb)@}}{2}\)

\(x = {@pm1*aa@}\) or \(x = {@pm2*bb@}\)
